re silenced or ignored. The author concludes that historians, or the historical guild, bear much responsibility for the unremembering of decolonization in Dutch collective memory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCollective memoryzNetherlands. 0aDecolonizationzNetherlands. 4aConflict and Peace. 4aContemporary History. 4aDutch and The Netherlands. 4aHeritage Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aSouth East Asia. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Western.2bisacsh  aCollective Memory, Dutch East Indies, Decolonization, Postcolonialism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074322708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048553075zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048553075zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048553075/original  a978-3-11-074322-7 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-074335-7 DG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA